const post = {
 title: 'What Is Screen Printing? How It Works, Where It Wins, Where It Doesn\'t',
 description:
 'Screen printing pushes ink through a mesh stencil onto fabric — durable, vivid, cost-effective at volume. Here\'s how the process actually works step-by-step, when to choose it over embroidery, and what fabrics and use cases it suits best.',
 category: 'Decoration Methods',
 readTime: '9 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/service-screen-printing.jpg',
 slug: 'what-is-screen-printing',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'What is screen printing?', a: 'Screen printing is a decoration method that pushes ink through a fine mesh stencil onto fabric, layer by layer for each color. The ink cures into the fibers so the design is durable, vivid, and washable. It\'s the standard for t-shirts, hoodies, and high-volume apparel runs.' },
 { q: 'How does screen printing work step by step?', a: 'A digital design is separated by color, each color burned onto a fine mesh screen as a stencil. The screen is mounted on a press; ink is flooded across the screen and pulled through the stencil onto the garment with a squeegee. After all colors are layered, the print is cured in a heat tunnel at ~320°F so the ink bonds permanently to the fabric.' },
 { q: 'Is screen printing better than embroidery?', a: 'For tees, hoodies, and large/colorful designs at volume — yes. Screen printing prints flat onto fabric so big designs and gradients work, and per-piece cost falls fast at quantity because most cost is in setup. Embroidery wins on polos, button-downs, hats, and any garment where a premium textured look matters more than design size or color.' },
 { q: 'What fabrics work best for screen printing?', a: 'Cotton and cotton-poly blends are the classic substrate — ink bonds well, cure time is short, results are crisp. 100% polyester requires special low-bleed inks to prevent dye migration. Performance fabrics (moisture-wicking poly) need water-based or polyester-formulated plastisol. Tyvek single-use coveralls can be screen-printed in cases of 25+.' },
 { q: 'How many colors can you screen print?', a: 'Modern automatic screen printing presses run 6-12 colors per design depending on the press. Each color is a separate screen with its own setup. Most commercial work shirts and crew tees run 1-3 colors to keep setup costs reasonable; high-detail designs go to 6+ colors.' },
 { q: 'How long does screen printed ink last?', a: 'Properly cured plastisol ink survives 50+ wash cycles without significant fading on most fabrics. Water-based inks fade slightly faster but feel softer. The most common cause of premature fading is undercured ink, not the printing method itself. See our piece on plastisol vs water-based for the full comparison.' },
 { q: 'How much does screen printing cost?', a: 'Per-piece cost depends on color count, garment cost, quantity, and setup. Setup is the biggest fixed cost — typically $20-40 per color. At 24+ pieces, per-piece printing typically runs $3-8 above the blank cost. At 200+ pieces, that drops dramatically because setup is amortized across more shirts.' },
]

